   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                              target="people.html#HenryIVKingofEngland">King Henry IV</ref>. The
                           First Part</title></hi>]. <note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"
                                    ><title><title><ref target="people.html#HenryIVKingofEngland"
                                    >King Henry IV</ref></title>. The First Part; A Historical Play,
                              In Five Acts; By <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">William
                                 Shakspeare</ref>. As Performed at the Theatre Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>. Printed
                              Under the Authority of the Managers From the Prompt Book. With Remarks
                              by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                           Inchbald</ref></title></hi>, London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees,
                        and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi rendition="#italics"><title
                              level="m">The British Theatre; or, A Collection of Plays, Which Are
                              Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury
                                 Lane</ref>, <ref target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent
                                 Garden</ref>, and <ref target="people.html#Haymarket"
                                 >Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the Authority of the Managers from
                              the Prompt Books. With Biographical and Critical Remarks, by <ref
                                 target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs. Inchbald.</ref></title></hi>
                        In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. II. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#HenryIVKingofEngland">King Henry IV</ref>.
                              First Part</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#HenryIVKingofEngland">King Henry IV</ref>.
                              Second Part</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Merchant of
                              Venice</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#HenryVKingofEngland">King Henry
                           V</ref></title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Much Ado About
                              Nothing</title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and
                        Orme, Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of this play was staged
                        in 1596 or 1597. Laura DeWitt and Mary A. Waters edited this essay for <hi
                           rendition="#italics">The Criticism Archive</hi>. </note>
                     <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </title>
               </bibl>
            </head>
            <p>This is a play which all men admire, and which most women dislike. Many revolting
               expressions in the comic parts, much boisterous courage in some of the graver scenes,
               together with <ref target="people.html#Falstaff">Falstaff</ref>'s unwieldy person,
               offend every female auditor; and whilst a facetious <ref
                  target="people.html#HenryVKingofEngland">Prince of Wales</ref> is employed in
               taking purses on the highway, a lady would rather see him stealing hearts at a ball,
               though the event might produce more fatal consequences.</p>

            <p>The great <ref target="people.html#PercyHenry">Percy</ref>, they confess, pays some
               attention to his wife, but still more to his horse: and, as the king was a rebel
               before he mounted the throne,<note>Prior to becoming king, <ref
                     target="people.html#HenryIVKingofEngland">Henry IV</ref> was in rebellion
                  against the throne of <ref target="people.html#RichardIIKingofEngland">Richard
                     II</ref>.</note> and all women are naturally loyal, they shudder at a crowned
               head leagued with a traitor's heart.</p>

            <p>With all these plausible objections, infinite entertainment and instruction, may be
               received from this drama, even by the most delicate readers. They will observe the
               pen of a faithful historian, as well as of a great poet; and they ought, surely, to
               be charmed with every character, as a complete copy of nature; admiring even the
               delinquency of them all, far beyond that false display of unsullied virtue, so easy
               for a bard to bestow upon the creatures of his fancy, when <fw type="sig"><hi
                     rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw><pb n="4"/>truth of description is sacrificed
               to brilliant impossibilities.</p>

            <p>The reader, who is too refined to laugh at the wit of <ref
                  target="people.html#Falstaff">Sir John</ref>, must yet enjoy <ref
                  target="people.html#PercyHenry">Hotspur</ref>'s picture of a coxcomb; and receive
               high delight from those sentences of self-reproach, and purpose of amendment, which
               occasionally drop from the lips of the youthful and royal profligate.</p>

            <p>If the licentious faults of old fashioned dialogue should here too frequently offend
               the strictly nice, they must, at least, confer the tribute of their praises upon
               every soliloquy. It is impossible for puritanism not to be merry, when <ref
                  target="people.html#Falstaff">Falstaff</ref> is ever found talking to himself; or
               holding discourse over the honoured dead. It is nearly as im possible [<hi
                  rendition="#italics">sic</hi>] for stupidity to be insensible of the merit of
               those sentiments, delivered by the prince, over the same extended corse; or, to be
               unmoved by various other beauties, with which this work abounds.</p>

            <p>In order to form a proper judgment of the manners and conversations of the characters
               in this play, and, to partake of their genuine spirit, the reader must keep in mind
               that the era, in which all those remarkable personages lived, thought, spoke, and
               acted, has now been passed more than four hundred years.&#8212;The play begins with
               the news of <ref target="people.html#PercyHenry">Hotspur</ref> having defeated the
               Scots, under the <ref target="people.html#DouglasArchibald">Earl of Douglas</ref>,
               which battle was fought on the fourteenth of September, 1402;<note><ref
                     target="people.html#PercyHenry">Hotspur</ref> defeated the Scottish forces at
                  the Battle of Homildon Hill in 1402, taking <ref
                     target="people.html#DouglasArchibald">Archibald Douglas</ref>, Earl of Douglas
                  and commander of the Scottish forces, as prisoner.</note> and it closes with the
               defeat and death of <ref target="people.html#PercyHenry">Hotspur</ref>, which
               happened on the twenty-first of July, 1403<note><ref target="people.html#PercyHenry"
                     >Hotspur</ref> was killed during the Battle of Shrewsbury, the rebel forces
                  greatly overwhelmed by the forces of the king, led by the <ref
                     target="people.html#HenryVKingofEngland">Prince of Wales</ref>. <ref
                     target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakespeare</ref> popularized the
                  legend that <ref target="people.html#PercyHenry">Hotspur</ref> was killed by the
                     <ref target="people.html#HenryVKingofEngland">Prince of Wales</ref> himself,
                  but historians believe that <ref target="people.html#PercyHenry">Hotspur</ref> was
                  likely cut down by an unknown soldier. The rebels fled after <ref
                     target="people.html#PercyHenry">Hotspur</ref> was struck
               down.</note>&#8212;thus comprising every event here introduced, within the time of
               ten months.</p>

            <pb n="5"/>
            <p>It will be vain to endeavour to prevent many tender-hearted readers, who sigh over
               the horrors of a battle, from wishing, that the prince's challenge to <ref
                  target="people.html#PercyHenry">Hotspur</ref> had produced the single combat he
               desired; and that the victory of the day had been so decided.</p>

            <p>Such tender and compassionate persons should not suffer their estimation of honour
               thus to sink into an equality with the cowardly <ref target="people.html#Falstaff"
                  >Falstaff</ref>'s; but they should call to mind&#8212;that, though it was, in
               ancient times, considered as a token of valour, for a prince at the head of an army,
               to challenge to single contest the chief warrior on the opposite side; yet, in modern
               days, when a powerful monarch threw his gauntlet down,<note>The throwing down of a
                  gauntlet at a person's feet served as a challenge for a duel. If the other party
                  picked up the gauntlet, they accepted the challenge.</note> to save the effusion
               of blood, this act of self-sacrifice was considered as a token of mere madness.</p>
            <fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 3</hi></fw>
         </div>
